\subsection{Command output}{

\verb{$render()} produces:
\itemize{
\item In single-constant mode (\verb{$multi_constant = FALSE}): \verb{xpiwe =;}
\item In multi-constant mode (\verb{$multi_constant = TRUE}):
\verb{xpiwe ( *\{proportion\} <\{max_ratio\};}
}
}

\subsection{Multi-constant mode}{

When \verb{$multi_constant} is \code{TRUE}, each character receives its own
concavity constant. In this mode:
\itemize{
\item \verb{$proportion} controls the assumed proportion of homoplasy for
missing values.
\item \verb{$max_ratio} limits how much constants can diverge between
characters.
}

Setting \verb{$multi_constant} to \code{FALSE} is equivalent to standard implied
weighting.
}

\subsection{Dependency and queue integration}{

\code{ExtendedImpliedWeightingCommand} handles the creation of the required
\link{ImpliedWeightingCommand} command. When calling \verb{$enqueue()}, it
automatically creates an \link{ImpliedWeightingCommand} configured with the same
\verb{$concavity_constant} (which adds it at priority \code{160} along with a
\code{HomoplasyTreeScoresCommand} at priority \code{710}), and then adds this command
at priority \code{230}. When using \code{\link[=set_weighting]{set_weighting()}}, both commands are created
and attached to the \link{TreeAnalysis} transparently.
}
}
